Install Consul and Envoy ( I have used Consul v1.21.5 and Envoy 1.32.2 )
https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/start/install 
I have used multipass here.

Run Consul:
consul agent -dev

Step 1: Start an "External" Service
python3 -m http.server 9001

Step 2: Register the External Service in the Catalog
Since this service is "outside" the mesh, we register it directly to the Consul catalog rather than through an agent.

Create external-service.json:

{
  "Node": "external-node",
  "Address": "127.0.0.1",
  "Service": {
    "ID": "legacy-app-1",
    "Service": "legacy-app",
    "Port": 9001
  }
}

Register it:
curl --request PUT --data @external-service.json localhost:8500/v1/catalog/register

Step 3: Create the Terminating Gateway Configuration
Now, tell Consul which services this gateway is allowed to represent.
Create terminating-gateway.hcl:

Kind = "terminating-gateway"
Name = "my-terminating-gateway"
Services = [
  {
    Name = "legacy-app"
  }
]

Write the config entry:
consul config write terminating-gateway.hcl

Step 4: Start the Gateway Process
In a new terminal, launch the Envoy proxy that will act as the Gateway. Consul will automatically generate the Envoy bootstrap config for you.

consul connect envoy -gateway=terminating -service my-terminating-gateway -register

Step 5: Test Connectivity from a Mesh Service
To prove it works, we’ll register a "test-client" and try to reach the legacy app through its allocated local port.

Register a client with an upstream:
Create test-client.json:

{
  "service": {
    "name": "test-client",
    "connect": {
      "sidecar_service": {
        "proxy": {
          "upstreams": [{
            "destination_name": "legacy-app",
            "local_bind_port": 1234
          }]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

Register and start its sidecar:
consul services register test-client.json
consul connect envoy -sidecar-for test-client -admin-bind "127.0.0.1:19001" &

Curl the upstream:
curl localhost:1234

###################################### API GW -> TERMINATING GW -> EXTERNAL SERVICE ############################################

The Traffic Flow:
User -> API Gateway (Port 8080) -> Terminating Gateway -> External Service (Port 9001)

Step 1: Register the API Gateway Configuration
You need to define how the API Gateway should listen for traffic and where it should route it.
Create api-gateway.hcl:

Kind = "api-gateway"
Name = "my-api-gateway"

# Define where the gateway listens
Listeners = [
  {
    Port     = 8080
    Protocol = "http"
    Name     = "http-listener"
  }
]

Apply it:
consul config write api-gateway.hcl

Step 2: Create an HTTP Route
This tells the API Gateway that any request hitting the listener should be sent to the legacy-app service (which is managed by your Terminating Gateway).

Create api-route.hcl:

Kind = "http-route"
Name = "legacy-route"

Parents = [
  {
    Kind        = "api-gateway"
    Name        = "my-api-gateway"
    SectionName = "http-listener"
  }
]

Rules = [
  {
    # Each rule can have filters and a list of services (backends)
    Filters = [
      {
        URLRewrite = {
          Path = "/"
        }
      }
    ]
    # 'Services' replaces 'BackendRefs'
    Services = [
      {
        Name = "legacy-app"
      }
    ]
  }
]

Apply it:
consul config write api-route.hcl

Step 3: Start the API Gateway Envoy Instance
In a new terminal, launch the Envoy process specifically for the API Gateway.

Note: Since you have the Terminating Gateway running on port 19000 (Envoy admin) and static client on 19001, you must use a different admin port for this one (e.g., 19002).

consul connect envoy -gateway=api -service my-api-gateway -register -admin-bind 127.0.0.1:19002

Step 4: Verification
Now, you can hit the API Gateway directly. It will route the traffic through the mesh to your Terminating Gateway, which then hits your Python server.

# Hit the API Gateway on port 8080
curl -v http://localhost:8080

O/P:
connect to 127.0.0.1 port 8080 from 127.0.0.1 port 57964 failed: Connection refused
* Failed to connect to localhost port 8080 after 1 ms: Couldn't connect to server
* Closing connection
curl: (7) Failed to connect to localhost port 8080 after 1 ms: Couldn't connect to server

Step 5: Create proxy-defaults.hcl

Kind      = "proxy-defaults"
Name      = "global"
Config {
  protocol = "http"
}

consul config write proxy-default.hcl 

Step 6: Re-Verification

# Hit the API Gateway on port 8080
curl -v http://localhost:8080

(This time you'll see the output)




